value.value: A multi-organism phenotype dealing with the process in which microorganisms attach to and grow on a surface and produce extracellular polymers that facilitate attachment and matrix formation.
An altered growth rate phenotype where the rate at which a cell or cells multiplies is decreased relative to a designated control.
An altered growth rate phenotype where the rate at which a cell or cells multiplies is increased relative to a designated control.
A population growth phenotype where the rate at which a cell or cells multiplies is altered relative to a designated control.
A growth phenotype concerning the rate at which the number of organisms or cells in a microbial population increases over time.
A microbial phenotype that affects the rate or extent of increase in the number of individuals in a microbial population as the result of sexual or asexual reproduction.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we recommend that it not be used for direct annotation. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A physical quality of the thermal energy of a system.
A quality of a physical entity that exists through action of continuants at the physical level of organisation in relation to other entities.
A physical quality that inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's amount of force per unit area it exerts.

definition.value: A quality which inheres in a continuant.

Relational qualities are qualities that hold between multiple entities. Normal (monadic) qualities such as the shape of a eyeball exist purely as a quality of that eyeball. A relational quality such as sensitivity to light is a quality of that eyeball (and connecting nervous system) as it relates to incoming light waves/particles.
A physical quality that inheres in an bearer by virtue of how that bearer interacts with electromagnetic radiation.
An EM radiation quality in which the EM radiation is within the fiat range of the spectrum visible deemed to be light.

value.value: A temperature which is relatively high.
A temperature which is relatively low.
A cellular quality inhering in a cell by virtue of whether the bearer exhibits the ability to move spontaneously.

definition.value: Term should be obsoleted and the GO term cellular motility should be used instead.
A quality that inheres in an bearer by virtue of how that bearer interacts with radiation.

value.value: A cellular motility which is lower relative to the normal or average.
A cellular motility which is higher relative to the normal or average.
A chemical treatment (EO:0007189) that induces stress.
A chemical stress treatment (EO:0001036) involving use of oxidative stress-inducing chemicals.
A chemical stress treatment (EO:0001036) involving use of osmotic stress-inducing chemicals.

The treatment involving an exposure to a given pressure of the atmosphere at a given point. Its measurement can be expressed in several ways. One is in millibars. Another is in inches or millimeters of mercury (Hg).

A portion of organism substance that is the product of an excretion process that will be eliminated from the body. An excretion process is elimination by an organism of the waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity

Multicellular anatomical structure that consists of many cells of one or a few types, arranged in an extracellular matrix such that their long-range organisation is at least partly a repetition of their short-range organisation.

Mucus is a bodily fluid consisting of a slippery secretion of the lining of the mucous membranes in the body. It is a viscous colloid containing antiseptic enzymes (such as lysozyme) and immunoglobulins. Mucus is produced by goblet cells in the mucous membranes that cover the surfaces of the membranes. It is made up of mucins and inorganic salts suspended in water.
Excretion that is the output of a kidney
Liquid components of living organisms. includes fluids that are excreted or secreted from the body as well as body water that normally is not.

definition.value: oxygen content with high oxygen concentration
oxygen content with low oxygen concentration
A physical quality that inheres in a bearer by virtue of the amount of hydrogen ions it contains
Experimental condition in which the pH of the water is lower than the pH of the controlled conditions.
Experimental condition in which the pH of the water is higher than the pH of the controlled conditions.
An ontology of biological or bioinformatics concepts and relations, a controlled vocabulary, structured glossary etc.
A graphical 2D tabular representation of gene expression data, typically derived from a DNA microarray experiment.
Image, hybridisation or some other data arising from a study of gene expression, typically profiling or quantification.
Biological or biomedical data has been rendered into an image, typically for display on screen.
Groupings of gene expression profiles according to a clustering algorithm.
